{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}
[[File:Bedini bugyal green.jpg|thumb|View of [[Bedni Bugyal]] on the way to [[Roopkund]]]]
'''Bugyals''' are alpine [[grassland|pasture lands]], or [[meadow]]s, in higher elevation range between {{Convert|3300|m}} and {{Convert|4000|m}} of the Himalayas in the Indian state of [[Uttarakhand]], where they are called "nature’s own gardens".{{Sfn|Tmh|p=93}} The topography of the terrain is either flat or sloped. The surface of these bugyals is covered with natural green grass and seasonal flowers. They are used by tribal herdsmen to graze their cattle. During the winter season the alpine meadows remain snow-covered. During summer months, the Bugyals present a riot of beautiful flowers and grass.  As bugyals constitute very fragile ecosystems, particular attention needs to be given for their conservation.{{Sfn|Tmh|p=93}}

Some of the notable bugyals are: [[Auli]] near [[Joshimath]], [[Garsi]], [[Kwanri]], [[Bedni Bugyal|Bedni]], [[Panwali and Kush Kalyan]], [[Dayara]] and [[Munsiyari]].<ref name="Tmh">{{cite book|author=Tmh|title=General Knowledge Digest 2010|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RyLmXWTKHXgC&pg=SA1-PA93|publisher=Tata McGraw-Hill Education|isbn=978-0-07-069939-7|pages=1–}}</ref>

==Auli Bugyal==
[[File:Ali bugyal2.jpg|thumb|View of Auli Bugyal]]
[[File:Auli hill station.jpg|thumb|Auli Bugyal during winter]]
[[File:20140822-Baidini Bugiyal 4664.jpg|thumb|Bedni Bugyal]]
Auli Bugyal in [[Chamoli district]],{{Sfn|Prasad|2009|p=62}} a highland pasture in the [[Garhwal Himalaya]]<ref name=Airport>{{cite book|title=The India Magazine of Her People and Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rQJuAAAAMAAJ|year=1987|publisher=A. H. Advani|page=93}}</ref> is known as the "Heaven Terrace".{{Sfn|Bisht|2008|p=61}} It lies in an elevation range of {{Convert|2500|-|3050|m}} with ski slopes located at an elevation of {{Convert|3048|m}}. On either side of the bugyal there are coniferous, [[oak]] and [[Cedrus deodara|deodar]] forests which limits the wind velocity to acceptable {{Convert|16|km}} for skiing.{{Sfn|Goyal|2014|p=151}} It is in the backdrop of [[Nanda Devi]] ({{Convert|7817|m}}), [[Kamet]] ({{Convert|7756|m}}), [[Mana Peak]] ({{Convert|7273|m}}), [[Dunagiri (mountain)|Dunagiri]] ({{Convert|7066|m}}), [[Hathi Parbat]] ({{Convert|6727|m}}), Bethantoli ({{Convert|6353|m}}) and [[Ghora Parbat]] peaks of the [[Himalayas]]. The trek to Auli passes through lush vegetation of apple orchards and oak forest.{{Sfn|Goyal|2014|p-151}}<ref>{{cite book|title=Sûrya India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=13lDAAAAYAAJ|year=1992|publisher=A. Anand.}}</ref> The ski slopes are said to better than those at [[Gulmarg]]. During the winter months (January to March) the slopes are covered with a mantle of snow which is spread over a width of {{Convert|3|km}},{{Sfn|Pandey|Pandey|2003|p=242}} and has a thickness {{Convert|8|-|10|ft}}.{{Sfn|Thapliyal|2005|p=215}} It is a skiing resort with modern skiing equipment.{{Sfn|Nigam|2002|p=139}} It is the venue of skiing festivities and the annual national championship of skiing held during February and March. It is {{Convert|13|km}} away from [[Joshimath]]. A {{Convert|500|m}} ski-lift system exists here which is believed to be the longest cable car ({{Convert|3.9|km}}) from Joshimath to the top most station at Gorson. It is the only location where artificial snow making system is provided to ensure that snow is present on the slopes for skiing. There are also two snow beaters which are used to make the snow slopes  fit for skiing.{{Sfn|Goyal|2014|p=151}}  As it is a winter sports centre and Vayudoot two airports have been planned in the region.<ref name=Airport/> R. V. Vernede, the British Deputy High Commissioner of the district during the British Raj had built a hut known as “Vernede” here at an elevation of {{Convert|11000|ft}}.{{Sfn|Prasad|2009|p=62}} It is under the control of the Garhwal Mandal Vikas Nigam Limited, which also provides for all skiing gear at site.{{Sfn|Pandey|Pandey|2003|p=242}}

Auli Bugyal is a very large alpine meadow which has expanse of grass land that covers several hundred acres of land, towards the sides of a wide ridge; Bedni Bugyal lies beyond this ridge. The meadows have vegetation of [[anemones]], ''[[Potentilla]]'', [[Pedicularis|lousewort]], [[Salvia roborowskii|wild ''Salvia'']] and [[thistles]]. Grazing by cattle and sheep is extensive. There are many trails that pass through the meadows.{{Sfn|Alter|2015|p=110}}

==Bedni Bugyal==
[[File:Bedini Kund near Bedini Bugyal, Chamoli, Uttarakhand, India.jpg|right|thumb|Bedini Kund in [[Bedni Bugyal]]]]
Meadows of the [[Bedni Bugyal]] in Chamoil district,{{Sfn|Goyal|2014|p=111}} are at an elevation of {{Convert|3350|m}}.{{Sfn|Betts|McCulloch|2014|p=120}} Alpine camps are established here for the pilgrims to visit the Rup Kund ('Kund' meaning "lake"), which is covered with snow for 10 months in a year.{{Sfn|Weare|2009|p=173}} From this camp to its west, views of the Himalayan peaks of the [[Gangotri]], the Trishul and the [[Nanda Ghunti]] provide a scenic backdrop. This budyal also has a small lake called Bedini Kund.{{Sfn|Weare|2009|p=173}}{{Sfn|Singhal|2013|p=173}} It is an artificial lake built with a concrete [[Levee|dyke]] by reclaiming a marshy wetland. There are two shrines here, one a small temple of Nanda Devi and the other a shrine for Latu. The temple is built with stones without using any mortar but moss growth is seen in the crevices. The Nanda Devi temple has two small carved stone images of the goddess and a pure white conch shell.{{Sfn|Alter|2015|p=111}} Bedni and Rup Kund are approached from [[Karnaprayag]].{{Sfn|Goyal|2014|p=111}} Medicinal herbs are found here.{{Sfn|Singh|2004|p=196}}

==Tungnath Bugyal==
[[File:Bugyal.jpg|thumb|View of a bugyal on the way to [[Tungnath]]]]
Tunganath Bugyal is at an elevation of {{Convert|3400|m}} and consists of moss cover over soil mantle on rock surface.{{Sfn|Rai|Upreti|2013|p=96}}

==Dayara Bugyal==
Dayara Bugyal, in [[Uttarkashi district]], meaning "high altitude meadow" is at an elevation of {{Convert|3408|m}}. The beautiful meadows are developed into [[Alpine skiing|ski slopes]] covering an area of {{Convert|28|km2}}.{{Sfn|Sharma|2008|p=262}} It has also been planned as a skiing resort.{{Sfn|Nigam|2002|p=139}} It is approached from Uttarkashi, up to village Raithal or village Barsu by road and further {{Convert|6|km}} by trekking.{{Sfn|Sharma|2008|p=262}}

==Other Bugyals==
On the Gangorti-Kedarnath trekking route the notable bugyals are Panwali ({{Convert|3963|m}}) and Kush-Kalyani.{{Sfn|Kohli|1983|pp=95&ndash;96}} Gorson Bugyal ({{Convert|11500| ft}}) is near Joshimath.{{Sfn|Yadav|1989|p=177}} In the alpine meadows of Uttarakhand other bugyals are Rajrambha, Marjhali, Rajthor, Darmithor, Bishanthor, Galpari, Sankalpa, Yangchari, and Shibu Gwar.{{Sfn|Rawat|2005|p=22}}jerai bugyal in almora district.

==Conservation issues==
Bugyal is a fragile [[ecosystem]] and it is essential to maintain a balance between [[ecology]] and [[environment (biophysical)|environment]]. In this context a court case was filed by the public objecting to erection of the prefab houses and by introducing non-biodegradable matter in the upper meadows of the bugyals by the tourism departments. It was averred that the peace and tranquility of the bugyals was getting affected. The court had ordered that the polluter must pay for the damage to environment based on [[Absolute liability|absolute liability principle]], which covered payment of damages to the affected people but also to compensate for all costs for restoration of the degraded environments.{{Sfn|Bhatt|2004|p=51}}

