'''Craig F. Bohren''' (born 1940) - American [[Atmospheric sciences|atmospheric scientist]] and physicist. Bohren wrote fundamental books on [[Scattering|light scattering]], [[atmospheric thermodynamics]], and [[radiative transfer]],<ref>{{cite book |last=Bohren |first=Craig |title=Fundamentals of Atmospheric Radiation: an Introduction with 400 Problems |publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]] |location=Chichester |year=2006 |isbn=978-3-527-40503-9}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Bohren |first=Craig |title=Absorption and Scattering of Light by Small Particles |publisher=Wiley |location=New York |year=1998 |isbn=978-0-471-29340-8}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Bohren |first=Craig |title=Atmospheric Thermodynamics |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |location=Oxford Oxfordshire |year=1998 |isbn=978-0-19-509904-1}}</ref> as well as [[popular science]] books on atmospheric optics.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bohren |first=Craig |title=Clouds in a Glass of Beer |publisher=[[Dover Publications]] |location=New York |year=2001 |isbn=978-0-486-41738-7}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Bohren |first=Craig |title=What Light through Yonder Window Breaks? |publisher=[[J. Wiley]] |location=London |year=1991 |isbn=978-0-471-52915-6}}</ref> He is Distinguished Professor Emeritus of Meteorology at [[Pennsylvania State University]]. He is an author of about 100 articles mostly on atmospheric optics, radiative transfer, and light scattering. His first atmospheric radiation teacher was Bruce Barkstrom. He is married to Nanette Malott Bohren.

